data.content:
This is a **timeout enforcement** pattern. `Thread.Abort`, `ThreadAbortException`, and `Thread.ResetAbort` all throw `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET 6+ (`SYSLIB0006`). The fix is cooperative cancellation with `CancellationToken`.

## Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        // CancellationTokenSource is IDisposable — always wrap in using
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        Task<T> task = Task.Run(work, cts.Token);

        try
        {
            // Task.WaitAsync throws OperationCanceledException when
            // the token fires, giving us our timeout behavior
            return task.WaitAsync(cts.Token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }

    // Prefer this async overload in new code
    public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
        Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout, CancellationToken externalToken = default)
    {
        using var cts = CancellationTokenSource
            .CreateLinkedTokenSource(externalToken);
        cts.CancelAfter(timeout);

        Task<T> task = Task.Run(work, cts.Token);

        try
        {
            return await task.WaitAsync(cts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (externalToken.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw; // caller cancelled — propagate as-is
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

## Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Why it matters |
|---------|---------------|
| **Work doesn't actually stop** | Cooperative cancellation only works if `work` checks the token. If it's a tight CPU loop or blocking I/O that ignores cancellation, the task keeps running in the background after timeout. |
| **Leaking `CancellationTokenSource`** | Always `using`/dispose it — it holds internal timers. |
| **Swallowing `OperationCanceledException`** | Use `when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)` to distinguish timeout from external cancellation. |
| **Uncooperative third-party code** | If `work` calls code you can't modify to accept a token, move it to a child `Process` and use `Process.Kill`. There is no in-process equivalent to `Thread.Abort`. |

## Making Work Cooperate

For the timeout to actually stop execution, the work delegate must participate:

```csharp
// Before (.NET Framework) — work didn't need to cooperate
executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(() => {
    while (true) { DoExpensiveThing(); } // Thread.Abort killed this
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));

// After (.NET 8) — work must check the token
executor.ExecuteWithTimeout((ct) => {
    while (!ct.IsCancellationRequested) { DoExpensiveThing(); }
    ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
    return result;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));
```

If you need that version, change the signature to `Func<CancellationToken, T>` and pass `cts.Token` into the delegate. This is the fundamental paradigm shift: **.NET Framework could forcibly kill threads; modern .NET requires the code to voluntarily check for cancellation.**
